{
  "answer": "**In Cynewulf's *Elene* (chapter 1), the passage occurs at the poem's opening, where Constantine, facing a massive barbarian invasion by the Huns, Hreth-Goths, Franks, and Hugas along the Danube, experiences a divine vision in a dream on the eve of battle.**[^1][^2]\n\nAs his army camps by the river, gripped by fear at the enemy's superior numbers, Constantine slumbers amid his thanes. A radiant angel appears, bearing the glowing cross (called the \"Rood,\" \"tree of glory,\" \"victory-tree,\" or \"beacon\") adorned with gold and gems. The angel instructs him: “By this sign, conquer,” promising victory over the foes.[^1][^2] Constantine awakens renewed, commands artisans to craft the *labarum* (a banner replicating the cross), and subsequently triumphs.[^3]\n\nThis adapts the historical legend of Constantine's vision before the Milvian Bridge (312 AD), here set against a Danube campaign, framing the poem's narrative of Elene (Helena) seeking the True Cross.\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-acdc07).\n\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-306e06).\n\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-86294a).",
